        <name>cameraSigma</name>
        <briefdescription>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>Let us consider an image <formula id="0">$I$</formula>. In the scale-space framework, we work with the scale-space image function <formula id="69">$ I : (x,y,\sigma) \mapsto (g_\sigma * I)\ (x,y) $</formula>, where <formula id="70">$g_\sigma$</formula> is the gaussian distribution with zero mean and standard deviation <formula id="47">$\sigma$</formula>.</para><para>We also denote by <formula id="71">$ I_\sigma : (x,y) \mapsto I(x,y,\sigma) $</formula> the image <formula id="0">$I$</formula> at scale <formula id="47">$\sigma$</formula>. Note that the real image is <formula id="72">$I_0: (x,y) \mapsto I(x,y)$</formula>. Because of the spatial sampling, the camera captures the real image <formula id="73">$I_0$</formula> with some blurring and the camera-acquired image is <formula id="74">$I_{\sigma_\textrm{camera}}$</formula>.</para><para>Here <ref refid="class_d_o_1_1_image_pyramid_params_1a7f000d11194059b31babe0cc8c75e475" kindref="member">cameraSigma()</ref> thus corresponds to <formula id="75">$\sigma_\textrm{camera}$</formula>. </para>        </detaileddescription>
        <inbodydescription>
        </inbodydescription>
        <location file="C:/Users/David/Desktop/GitHub/DO-CV/src/DO/ImageProcessing/ImagePyramid.hpp" line="45" bodyfile="C:/Users/David/Desktop/GitHub/DO-CV/src/DO/ImageProcessing/ImagePyramid.hpp" bodystart="45" bodyend="45"/>
      </memberdef>
      <memberdef kind="function" id="class_d_o_1_1_image_pyramid_params_1af34d613c4c3b7615bf0eedecf533aa2d" prot="public" static="no" const="yes" explicit="no" inline="yes" virt="non-virtual">
        <type>double</type>
        <definition>double initSigma</definition>
        <argsstring>() const </argsstring>
        <name>initSigma</name>
        <briefdescription>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>The image pyramid discretizes image function <formula id="76">$(x,y,\sigma) \mapsto I(x,y,\sigma)$</formula> in the scale-space. With the discretization, the image pyramid will consist of a stack of blurred images <formula id="77">$(I_{\sigma_i})_{1 \leq i \leq N}$</formula>.</para><para>Here <ref refid="class_d_o_1_1_image_pyramid_params_1af34d613c4c3b7615bf0eedecf533aa2d" kindref="member">initSigma()</ref> corresponds to <formula id="78">$\sigma_0$</formula>. </para>        </detaileddescription>
        <inbodydescription>
        </inbodydescription>
        <location file="C:/Users/David/Desktop/GitHub/DO-CV/src/DO/ImageProcessing/ImagePyramid.hpp" line="54" bodyfile="C:/Users/David/Desktop/GitHub/DO-CV/src/DO/ImageProcessing/ImagePyramid.hpp" bodystart="54" bodyend="54"/>
      </memberdef>
      <memberdef kind="function" id="class_d_o_1_1_image_pyramid_params_1a464bc11f7f5ed7a5b78a77b708504145" prot="public" static="no" const="yes" explicit="no" inline="yes" virt="non-virtual">
        <type>double</type>
        <definition>double scaleGeomFactor</definition>
        <argsstring>() const </argsstring>
        <name>scaleGeomFactor</name>
        <briefdescription>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>The sequence <formula id="79">$ (\sigma_i)_{1 \leq i \leq N} $</formula> follows a geometric progression, i.e., <formula id="80">$\sigma_i = k^i \sigma_0$</formula>.</para><para>Laplacians of Gaussians <formula id="81">$ \nabla^2 I_{\sigma} $</formula> can be approximated efficiently with differences of Gaussians <formula id="82">$ I_{k\sigma} - I_{\sigma} $</formula> for each <formula id="83">$ \sigma = \sigma_i $</formula>*without needing to renormalize*.</para><para>Indeed: <formula id="84">\begin{eqnarray*} \frac{\partial I_\sigma}{\partial \sigma} &amp;=&amp; \sigma \nabla^2 I_\sigma \\ I_{k\sigma} - I_{\sigma} &amp;\approx&amp; (k-1) \sigma^2 \nabla^2 I_\sigma \end{eqnarray*}</formula></para><para>Here <ref refid="class_d_o_1_1_image_pyramid_params_1a464bc11f7f5ed7a5b78a77b708504145" kindref="member">scaleGeomFactor()</ref> corresponds to the value <formula id="85">$ k $</formula>. </para>        </detaileddescription>
        <inbodydescription>
        </inbodydescription>
        <location file="C:/Users/David/Desktop/GitHub/DO-CV/src/DO/ImageProcessing/ImagePyramid.hpp" line="71" bodyfile="C:/Users/David/Desktop/GitHub/DO-CV/src/DO/ImageProcessing/ImagePyramid.hpp" bodystart="71" bodyend="71"/>
      </memberdef>
      <memberdef kind="function" id="class_d_o_1_1_image_pyramid_params_1a082021f63e30549dcdfc683acf6107db" prot="public" static="no" const="yes" explicit="no" inline="yes" virt="non-virtual">
        <type>int</type>
        <definition>int numScalesPerOctave</definition>
        <argsstring>() const </argsstring>
        <name>numScalesPerOctave</name>
        <briefdescription>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>The smoothed image <formula id="86">$I_{2\sigma}$</formula> is equivalent to the downsampled image <formula id="87">$I_{\sigma}$</formula>. Because of this observation, a pyramid of gaussians is divided into octaves.</para><para>We call an octave a stack of <formula id="29">$S$</formula> blurred images <formula id="88">$I_{\sigma_i}$</formula> separated by a constant factor <formula id="89">$k$</formula> in the scale space, i.e., <formula id="90">$ \sigma_{i+1} = k \sigma_i $</formula>. The number of scales in each octave is the integer <formula id="29">$S$</formula> such that <formula id="91">$k^S \sigma = 2 \sigma$</formula>, i.e., <formula id="92">$ k= 2^{1/S} $</formula>. </para>        </detaileddescription>
        <inbodydescription>
        </inbodydescription>
